## Task 4

TCP/IP Model

1. Definition
The TCP/IP (Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol) model is the standard networking model used on the Internet. It consists of 4 layers that define how data is transmitted, routed, and received between devices.
2. Important Points
- The TCP/IP model has 4 layers:
  Application
  Transport
  Internet
  Network Interface
- It is the practical networking model used in real-world communication and forms the basis of the Internet.
- The Application layer combines the functions of the Application, Presentation, and Session layers of the OSI model.
- The Internet layer is equivalent to the Network layer in the OSI model and uses the Internet Protocol (IP) for logical addressing and routing.
- The Network Interface layer combines the Data Link and Physical layers of the OSI model.
- Uses the same encapsulation and de-encapsulation process as the OSI model.
- Each layer adds a header during encapsulation and removes it during de-encapsulation.
- Based on a suite of networking protocols, including TCP, IP, UDP, HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SMTP, DNS, DHCP, and more.

TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)
  
Definition
- TCP is a connection-oriented, reliable transport protocol that ensures data is delivered accurately, completely, and in the correct order.
Important Points
- Establishes a connection before transmitting data.
- Uses the Three-Way Handshake to create a reliable connection.
- Provides error detection and error recovery.
- Retransmits lost or corrupted packets.
- Ensures packets arrive in the correct order.
- Uses acknowledgements (ACKs) to confirm successful delivery.
- Performs flow control and congestion control.
- Used for HTTP/HTTPS, FTP, Email (SMTP/IMAP/POP3), SSH, and other applications requiring reliability.

Three-Way Handshake

Definition
- The Three-Way Handshake is the process TCP uses to establish a reliable connection between a client and a server before data transfer begins.
- Steps
  SYN → Client sends a synchronization request to the server.
  SYN-ACK → Server acknowledges the request and sends its own synchronization request.
  ACK → Client acknowledges the server, and the connection is established.

Flow:

Client                  Server
  SYN   -------------->
       <--------------  SYN + ACK
  ACK   -------------->
Connection Established

TCP/IP vs OSI Model (layers)

OSI Model(7)	    TCP/IP Model(4)
Application	      Application
Presentation	    Application
Session	          Application
Transport	        Transport
Network	          Internet
Data Link	        Network Interface
Physical	        Network Interface

History 

- TCP/IP was developed by the U.S. Department of Defense (DoD) in 1982.
- It became the standard protocol suite for Internet communication.
- The OSI Model was later developed by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
- TCP/IP is used in real-world networking, while the OSI model is mainly used for learning, designing, and troubleshooting networks.

